USER MANAGEMENT :
Sudo : sudo is a program for Unix-like computer operating systems
that enables users to run programs with the security privileges of
another user, by default the superuser.
THADOMAL SHAHANI ENGINEERING COLLEGE
DEPARTMENT OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY
Sudo -l: will print out the commands allowed (and forbidden) the user
on the current host.
THADOMAL SHAHANI ENGINEERING COLLEGE
DEPARTMENT OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY
Sudo -v: If, given the -v (validate) option, sudo will update the user’s
timestamp, prompting for the user’s password if necessary.
Sudo -k: The -k (kill) option to sudo invalidates the user’s timestamp.
So, the next time sudo is run a password will be required.
Sudo -s: The -s option runs the shell specified by the SHELL
environment variable if it is set
